Description

This case documents a Beekeeper Protocol investigation into suspicious discovery-related process execution observed in Sysmon Event ID 1 telemetry.
Objective:
Determine whether observed command execution reflects legitimate administrative behavior or activity that deviates from established baseline process patterns.
Scenario:
Execution of discovery-related commands was reviewed, with particular attention to ipconfig.exe and associated process lineage. Analysis focused on execution context, parent-child relationships, and alignment with known-good administrative behavior.
Analysis Approach:
-Review Sysmon Event ID 1 process creation telemetry.
-Validate parent-child process relationships.
-Compare observed execution against baseline administrative activity.
-Determine whether command usage is normal, suspicious, or indicative of compromise.
-Map observed behavior to relevant MITRE ATT&CK techniques.
MITRE ATT&CK mapping:
-T1016.001- Internet Connection Discovery
-T1033- System Owner/User Discovery
-T1082- System Information Discovery
-T1204- User executrion
Initial Assessment:
Discovery commands may be legitimate in isolation, but context determines investigative value. Command execution, parent process lineage, and behavioral consistency with baseline must be validated before escalation.
Beekeeper Insight:
It is not the command alone that matters- it is the context around the command,. A legitimate tool executed from an unexpected parent process may indicate reconnaissance or early-stage adversary activity.
Current Status:
Investigation in progress. Parent-child relationships, command frequency, and execution context require validation against baseline before final determination.
Precursor Activity:
Initial access vector potentially linked to social engineering activity documented in:
Operation Poisoned Nectar: Vishing-Based Initial Access.
This reinforces the importance of correlating user-driven events with endpoint telemetry.
